\pard\plain \s2\qj \b\f16 {Humanoid Derivatives\par 
}\pard\plain \qj \f16\fs20 \tab Substitution of humanoid derivatives for beast derivatives in compounds used by humanoids generally produces a more effective compound. Further, living or fresh specimens yield derivatives of superior strength.\par 
\tab Some renewable substances (blood, glandular extracts, etc.) can be obtained from living specimens of dwarf, elf, halfling, and human without harming the individual.\par 
\tab Type of Reagent: Common\par 
\tab Cost: 1/-\par 
\tab Availability: Common\par 
\tab From Scratch: 1d6+3 measures can be obtained from a single individual; process requires 1d3 hours.\par 
\tab Examples:\par 
\tab fresh [species] glandular extracts\par 
\tab fresh [species] blood\par 
\par 
\tab Many tissues of dwarf, elf, halfling, and human cannot be collected without great harm to the individual. Pragmatic, moral, and ethical considerations limit the supply of derivatives of living and fresh humanoids in civilized society. 
Alchemists may purchase remains of humanoids to render for derivatives, wherever possible directly from relatives, who are permitted by law to sell a deceased\rquote s
 remains, or from the Watch, street cleaners, and keepers of poor hostelries, or, in extremis, from grave robbers. 
The Cult of Morr proscribes the sale of cultists for such purposes, but poor folk may prefer the prospect of a few gold coin in this world to the promise of eternal rest in the next. \par 
\tab In remote and wilderness regions, and on the black market, such humanoid derivatives may be easily obtained and inexpensive. The Guild a
lso seems to have ample resources available to Guild members and academies for experimentation and priority projects.\par 
\tab Type of Reagent: Extraordinary\par 
\tab Cost: 1 GC\par 
\tab Availability: Common\par 
\tab From Scratch: 1 specimen yields 1d10+10 measures; process requires 1d6+3 hours.\par 
\tab Examples:\par 
